---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
import '../../styles/course.css';
import LessonPage from '../../components/course/LessonPage';
import GatePanel from '../../components/assessment/GatePanel';
---

<BaseLayout title="Case Study: Gemma 4 Attention Path">
  <LessonPage lessonId="L40" client:load>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Question</div>
      <div class="lesson-question">How does Gemma 4 handle attention?</div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Intuition</div>
      <p>
        Full self-attention is powerful but expensive: every token attends to every other token, so cost scales quadratically with sequence length. Gemma 4 solves this by using two types of attention layers that alternate through the model:
      </p>
      <ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: var(--space-3) 0;">
        <li style="display: flex; gap: var(--space-3); padding: var(--space-2) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          <span style="color: var(--sem-attention); font-weight: 600; min-width: 160px;">Full attention</span>
          <span style="color: var(--ink-secondary);">Every token attends to every other token in the context. Used in a minority of layers.</span>
        </li>
        <li style="display: flex; gap: var(--space-3); padding: var(--space-2) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          <span style="color: var(--sem-ffn); font-weight: 600; min-width: 160px;">Sliding Window Attention (SWA)</span>
          <span style="color: var(--ink-secondary);">Each token only attends to a fixed-size local window of nearby tokens. Used in the majority of layers.</span>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        SWA layers are much cheaper because the attention matrix is sparse &mdash; each row only has entries for tokens within the window. The occasional full-attention layer ensures the model can still capture long-range dependencies.
      </p>
      <p>
        On top of this, Gemma 4 uses <strong>shared-KV layers</strong>. Only a subset of layers (controlled by a config parameter) compute their own K/V projections. The remaining layers skip K/V projection entirely and reuse the KV cache from the nearest earlier layer that has its own K/V. This dramatically reduces memory usage and compute — shared layers need no K/V weight matrices and write nothing to the cache.
      </p>
      <p>
        The builder code handles this by checking <code>has_kv(il)</code> for each layer. If true, the layer projects fresh K and V. If false, it passes <code>nullptr</code> for K/V, telling <code>build_attn()</code> to read from an earlier layer's cache entry. The attention computation itself is the same &mdash; only the cache source and the window mask differ.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Toy Example</div>
      <div class="toy-example">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
          A 6-layer Gemma 4 model with window size 3 and layers [SWA, SWA, full, SWA, SWA, full]:
        </p>
        <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">sequence:</span> [A, B, C, D, E, F, G, H] &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">(8 tokens)</span>
          </div>
          <div style="padding-left: var(--space-4); border-left: 2px solid var(--sem-ffn-dim); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            <span style="color: var(--sem-ffn);">SWA layer (window=3):</span> token H attends to [F, G, H] only
          </div>
          <div style="padding-left: var(--space-4); border-left: 2px solid var(--sem-attention-dim); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            <span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">Full layer:</span> token H attends to [A, B, C, D, E, F, G, H]
          </div>
          <div style="margin-top: var(--space-3); color: var(--ink-tertiary);">
            If layers 0 and 2 have fresh KV (has_kv=true), layers 1,3,4,5 reuse earlier caches. Only 2 KV entries stored instead of 6.
          </div>
        </div>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-3);">
          Shared-KV layers avoid K/V projection compute and cache storage &mdash; significant savings when most layers are shared.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Shapes</div>
      <div class="shape-card">
        <div>Full attention: Q &times; K<sup>T</sup> &rarr; [n_tokens, n_tokens] &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">(all-to-all)</span></div>
        <div>SWA attention: Q &times; K<sup>T</sup> &rarr; [n_tokens, window_size] &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">(local only)</span></div>
        <div style="margin-top: var(--space-2);">Shared SWA KV cache: [window_size, d_k] &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">(one cache for all SWA layers)</span></div>
        <div>Per-layer full KV cache: [n_tokens, d_k] &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">(one cache per full-attention layer)</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Math</div>
      <p>The attention math is unchanged &mdash; the difference is which keys and values are visible:</p>
      <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm); background: var(--surface-3); padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); border-radius: var(--radius-sm); margin: var(--space-3) 0;">
        <div style="color: var(--sem-attention);">Full: scores = Q &sdot; K<sup>T</sup> / &radic;d_k &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">(all positions)</span></div>
        <div style="color: var(--sem-ffn);">SWA: scores = Q &sdot; K<sub>window</sub><sup>T</sup> / &radic;d_k &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">(local window only)</span></div>
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">Positions outside the SWA window are masked to &minus;&infin; before softmax.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">The Real Code</div>
      <p>
        The Gemma 4 iSWA builder splits each layer's attention path based on whether the layer has its own K/V projections or reuses an earlier layer's KV cache. Here is the branching logic:
      </p>
      <div style="background: var(--surface-3); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4); margin: var(--space-4) 0; overflow-x: auto;">
        <pre style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-xs); line-height: 1.7; margin: 0; color: var(--ink-secondary);" set:html={`<code><span style="color: var(--ink-primary);">// self-attention: branch on whether this layer has its own K/V</span>
<span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">if (hparams.has_kv(il))</span> {
    <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">// KV layer: project K and V from the normed hidden state</span>
    ggml_tensor * Kcur = build_lora_mm(model.layers[il].wk, cur);
    ggml_tensor * Vcur = model.layers[il].wv
                            ? build_lora_mm(model.layers[il].wv, cur)
                            : Kcur; <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">// if no v_proj, reuse K as V</span>

    <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">// Reshape to [d_head, n_kv_heads, n_tokens]</span>
    Kcur = ggml_reshape_3d(ctx0, Kcur, n_embd_head, n_head_kv, n_tokens);
    Vcur = ggml_reshape_3d(ctx0, Vcur, n_embd_head, n_head_kv, n_tokens);

    <span style="color: var(--sem-token);">// Gemma 4 normalizes K and V before RoPE — unusual!</span>
    Kcur = <span style="color: var(--sem-token);">build_norm</span>(Kcur, model.layers[il].attn_k_norm, ...);
    Vcur = <span style="color: var(--sem-token);">ggml_rms_norm</span>(ctx0, Vcur, hparams.f_norm_rms_eps);

    <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">// Apply RoPE to K (Q was already rotated above)</span>
    Kcur = ggml_rope_ext(ctx0, Kcur, inp_pos, freq_factors, ...);

    cur = <span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">build_attn</span>(inp_attn, model.layers[il].wo, nullptr,
            Qcur, Kcur, Vcur, nullptr, nullptr, nullptr,
            hparams.f_attention_scale, il);
} <span style="color: var(--sem-ffn);">else</span> {
    <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">// Shared-KV layer: no K/V projections, reuses earlier cache</span>
    cur = <span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">build_attn</span>(inp_attn,
            model.layers[il].wo, nullptr,
            Qcur, <span style="color: var(--sem-ffn);">nullptr, nullptr</span>, nullptr, nullptr, nullptr,
            hparams.f_attention_scale, il);
}</code>`} />
      </div>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-xs); color: var(--ink-ghost); margin-top: var(--space-2);">
        Source: ggml-org/llama.cpp @ <code>94ca829b</code> &mdash; <code>src/models/gemma4-iswa.cpp</code>
      </p>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary); margin-top: var(--space-3);">
        The key difference: when <code>has_kv(il)</code> is true, the layer computes its own K and V from the hidden state and writes them to a cache. When false, K and V are <code>nullptr</code> &mdash; the <code>build_attn</code> helper reads K/V from a shared cache written by an earlier layer. The Q projection always runs; only K/V are conditionally shared.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Implementation Hook</div>
      <div class="impl-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          The <code>build_attn_inp_kv_iswa()</code> call sets up the KV cache infrastructure that makes shared layers work. SWA layers and full-attention layers use different attention masks (windowed vs. causal), but the <code>build_attn()</code> call itself is identical &mdash; the infrastructure handles the difference.
        </p>
        <div class="file-path"><a href="https://github.com/ggml-org/llama.cpp/blob/94ca829b6001019622c0f67fcd48e9ec6bd7dce8/src/models/gemma4-iswa.cpp#L30" target="_blank" rel="noopener">src/models/gemma4-iswa.cpp — layer loop (L30)</a></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Performance Hook</div>
      <div class="perf-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          SWA layers are cheaper in two ways: (1) the attention computation is O(n &times; w) instead of O(n&sup2;), where w is the window size, and (2) sharing one KV cache across all SWA layers reduces memory bandwidth during decode. For long sequences, the memory savings from shared-KV can be the difference between fitting in GPU memory and not.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Check Yourself</div>
      <GatePanel
        client:load
        lessonId="L40"
        gateStrength="hard"
        questions={[
          {
            id: 'L40-q1',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'What is the difference between SWA layers and full-attention layers in Gemma 4?',
            tag: 'conceptual',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'SWA layers use smaller weight matrices than full-attention layers', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'SWA layers only attend to a local window of nearby tokens, while full-attention layers attend to all tokens', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: 'SWA layers skip the attention step entirely and only run FFN', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'SWA (Sliding Window Attention) restricts each token to attending only within a fixed-size local window. Full-attention layers allow all-to-all token interactions. Both perform the same Q-K-V attention math — the difference is which keys are visible.',
          },
          {
            id: 'L40-q2',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'In the Gemma 4 builder, what does has_kv(il) returning false mean for that layer?',
            tag: 'conceptual',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'The layer uses a different attention algorithm', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'The layer skips K/V projection and reuses an earlier layer\'s KV cache entry instead of computing its own', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: 'The layer has no attention at all — it only runs FFN', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'When has_kv is false, the layer passes nullptr for K and V to build_attn. The attention function then reads K/V from the nearest earlier layer that computed fresh K/V. This saves both the projection compute and the cache storage for that layer.',
          },
          {
            id: 'L40-q3',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'Why does Gemma 4 still include some full-attention layers instead of using SWA everywhere?',
            tag: 'conceptual',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'Full-attention layers are needed for the FFN to work correctly', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'SWA cannot capture long-range dependencies beyond the window, so occasional full-attention layers provide global context', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: 'Full-attention layers are faster than SWA layers for short sequences', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'SWA is limited to local context within the window. Without any full-attention layers, information from distant tokens could never directly influence the current position. A few full-attention layers ensure long-range dependencies are captured.',
          },
        ]}
      />
    </div>

  </LessonPage>
</BaseLayout>
